const faqSchema = {"@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "FAQPage", "mainEntity": [{"@type": "Question", "name": "Why Do Traditional Lenders Struggle with Self-Employed Investor Income?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The first challenge was income documentation complexity. As a real estate agent, Rachel earned commission income that varied dramatically based on transaction closings. Some months she closed multiple deals generating substantial income. Other months she had few closings despite working equally hard on pipeline development. Her annual income was strong, but monthly and quarterly income showed significant variation that traditional lenders viewed skeptically."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How Do Rental Property Portfolios Complicate Traditional Mortgage Qualification?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The second obstacle was portfolio complexity. With three existing rental properties, Rachel's personal tax returns were complicated\u2014showing rental income, expenses, depreciation, and various deductions that reduced her taxable income while building wealth. This tax-efficient structure was smart financially but made her appear to earn less than she actually did on paper, reducing her borrowing capacity with traditional lenders."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What Documentation Do Traditional Investment Property Loans Require?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The third challenge was documentation burden and timeline delays. Rachel competed for investment properties against other investors\u2014including cash buyers and investors with faster financing. Traditional mortgage processes requiring extensive income documentation, multiple underwriter reviews, and careful verification took substantial time. Rachel had lost several excellent investment opportunities to competitors who could close faster, even though she was financially capable and qualified."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Why Does